  <content>
    <title>VUI Testing Best Practices</title>

    <summary>VUI testing across three accuracy tiers with deterministic assertions and LLM-judge scoring.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Voice interfaces fail in ways that standard usability testing misses: ASR provider upgrades shift accuracy silently, no-input and barge-in edge cases break state machines, and naturalness degrades invisibly when prompts are repeated verbatim on retry. Separating test tiers (deterministic vs LLM-judge) and tracking ASR, NLU, and dialog completion independently isolates where regressions originate.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch validation of an Alexa Skill, Google Action, or custom voice agent: stress-test intent recognition + dialog flow before certification.</item>
        <item>Multilingual/accent expansion: regression-test ASR accuracy and prompt naturalness across locales using batched audio fixtures.</item>
        <item>Continuous regression: every voice prompt or NLU model change re-runs a corpus of utterance fixtures and asserts intent + slot extraction accuracy.</item>
        <item>Field testing prep: scripted noise-injection runs before recruiting real users.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Voice is a single shortcut, not a primary interface (e.g., a "tap-and-hold to speak" search): standard usability testing covers it.</item>
        <item>You don't yet have a working dialog model — start with Wizard-of-Oz prototyping, not test automation.</item>
        <item>Single-turn command testing only: an NLU benchmark (intent classification F1) is enough; a full VUI test suite is overkill.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="testing-layers">
      <p>Five layers in order of granularity: unit (intent recognition accuracy), integration (dialog flow completion), user (real-world usability), stress (noise, interruptions, edge cases), accessibility (accent diversity, speech impairment).</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Track three accuracy tiers separately: ASR word-error rate, NLU intent+slot F1, and dialog task completion. A regression in only one tier tells you exactly where to look.</statement>
        <rationale>Aggregating across tiers hides the root cause. ASR regression means transcription changed; NLU regression means intent model changed; dialog regression means state machine changed. Each has a different fix.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="key-metrics">
      <list>
        <item>Intent accuracy: % correct intent detection per utterance</item>
        <item>Task completion: % of users completing their goal end-to-end</item>
        <item>Error rate: dialog failures per conversation</item>
        <item>Word error rate (WER): ASR transcription accuracy</item>
        <item>User satisfaction: post-interaction survey (CSAT or 1-5 scale)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="two-tier-suite">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a two-tier test suite: tier 1 = deterministic assertions over scripted utterance fixtures (intent, slot, dialog-state outcomes); tier 2 = LLM-judge scoring for naturalness, error recovery, and goal completion against a rubric. Never mix the two tiers' outputs into a single pass/fail count.</statement>
        <rationale>Deterministic assertions catch regressions objectively. LLM-judge scoring evaluates qualitative properties that assertions cannot reach. Mixing them produces an opaque aggregate that hides which type of regression occurred.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pin ASR model versions in CI. Provider-side ASR upgrades silently shift WER and break tests overnight.</statement>
        <rationale>Cloud ASR providers update models without notice. A passing suite built against model v1 can fail entirely against model v2 with no code changes. Version-pin prevents silent shifts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="templates/test-plan.md">VUI test plan template</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="corpus-construction">
      <rule>
        <statement>Build the utterance corpus from real anonymized user logs first; synthesize LLM variants second. Pure LLM-generated corpora over-represent grammatical, in-domain phrasings and miss real-user degradation.</statement>
        <rationale>Real logs capture the messy, elliptical, code-switched, and misspelled phrasings that actual users produce. LLMs trained on clean text generate clean test cases that produce falsely high accuracy numbers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Include barge-in tests (user interrupts mid-prompt) and no-input tests (timeout) in every suite. These break dialog state machines more reliably than utterance variation.</statement>
        <rationale>Barge-in and timeout edge cases break state machines at the interrupt handler level, independent of intent recognition. They are structurally different failures requiring different fixes.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="noise-injection">
      <rule>
        <statement>Mix clean utterances with ambient noise (TV, traffic, cafe) at multiple SNR levels (20dB, 10dB, 5dB) for stress testing. Use ffmpeg for mixing.</statement>
        <rationale>Synthetic noise injection is imperfect (misses room acoustics and beamforming) but captures most recognizable degradation modes: background speech, low SNR, frequency masking.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="templates/stress-corpus.sh">Shell script: mix utterances with noise at 3 SNR levels</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="ci-tiering">
      <rule>
        <statement>Tier the suite: smoke (10 utterances, every commit) → full (nightly) → field-replay (release). Do not run the full LLM-judge sweep on every commit — cost and latency are non-trivial.</statement>
        <rationale>A 1000-utterance x 3-noise x 2-locale x LLM-judge sweep is expensive. Tiering keeps commit feedback fast while ensuring thorough coverage before release.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run the same suite in at least two locales even for monolingual launches. Reveals locale-leaking copy and fallback bugs.</statement>
        <rationale>Locale bugs appear at locale boundaries: hardcoded English fallbacks, date/number format assumptions, and ASR models with uneven locale coverage. Single-locale suites miss all of these.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-judge-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM judge sees the expected answer when scoring naturalness — anchoring bias inflates scores.</description>
        <reason>Score naturalness blind, then compute correctness separately. Judges with access to expected answers rate responses as more natural when they are also correct, masking naturalness failures in correct responses.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using absolute 1-5 naturalness scores instead of pairwise comparison.</description>
        <reason>Absolute LLM scores are unreliable across sessions. Pairwise comparison ("Is A or B more natural?") produces more consistent results and surfaces meaningful differences between prompt variants.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="fixture-and-privacy-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using the same TTS vendor for test fixtures as for product output — produces false-high naturalness scores.</description>
        <reason>Same-vendor TTS creates circular evaluation: the LLM judge finds familiar prosody patterns more natural. Use a different TTS engine for fixture generation than for product rendering.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending raw user-recorded audio to a cloud LLM judge.</description>
        <reason>Raw audio may contain PII, bystander voices, and background conversations. Always transcribe locally first, redact PII, then judge the text. Never pass raw audio to an external model.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="infrastructure-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running the full LLM-judge suite concurrently without concurrency caps, hitting 429 rate limits that cause silent test passes.</description>
        <reason>429 responses can be swallowed as empty results rather than errors. Cap concurrency at provider rate limits and treat any 429 as a test failure, not a skip.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <reference path="templates/llm-judge-prompt.txt">Per-turn LLM judge prompt scoring intent_match, naturalness, brevity, error_recovery</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="where-it-fails">
      <list>
        <item>Synthetic TTS test audio does not replicate real human prosody — accuracy numbers are optimistic versus production traffic.</item>
        <item>Background-noise injection in test fixtures misses physical room acoustics (reverb, multi-mic beamforming) that smart speakers actually face.</item>
        <item>Long-context retention bugs only surface in conversations >10 turns; most automated suites stop at 3-5.</item>
        <item>LLM-judges of "did the assistant respond appropriately?" are biased toward verbose, polite responses and miss curtness/friction issues.</item>
        <item>Privacy: voice fixtures with real PII cannot be replayed in cloud ASR — leaks customer data.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Run a two-tier suite: (1) deterministic test cases over scripted utterance fixtures asserting intent/slot/dialog-state machine outcomes; (2) LLM-judge tier scoring response naturalness, error recovery, and goal completion against a rubric. A coordinator subagent picks which tier each test belongs in, runs them in parallel, and produces a report keyed by feature + locale + noise condition. Human reviewers sign off any LLM-judge regression before promoting to production.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>faion-ux-researcher-agent — designs the test corpus (utterance variants, persona-based scenarios, edge cases).</item>
        <item>faion-testing-developer (from free/dev/testing-developer) — wires fixtures into pytest/jest harness, manages CI integration.</item>
        <item>faion-accessibility-specialist — reviews coverage for accent diversity, speech impairment patterns, hearing-related response cues.</item>
        <item>faion-llm-integration agent (from geek/ai/llm-integration) — runs the LLM-judge tier with stable rubric prompts.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <p>LLM-judge per turn:</p>
      <prompt purpose="llm-judge"><![CDATA[
Conversation so far: {transcript}
User utterance: "{utterance}"
Assistant response: "{response}"
Score (1-5) on: intent_match, naturalness, brevity, error_recovery.
Return JSON. Penalize if response invents facts not in {kb}.
      ]]></prompt>

      <p>Corpus generator:</p>
      <prompt purpose="corpus-generator"><![CDATA[
Generate 30 phrasings of the intent "{intent}" varying formality, length, and dialect (en-US, en-GB, en-IN). Include 5 ungrammatical variants real users might say.
      ]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>ask (Alexa Skills Kit CLI) — Invoke skills, run simulator, fetch logs. npm i -g ask-cli; https://developer.amazon.com/en-US/docs/alexa/smapi/quick-start-alexa-skills-kit-command-line-interface.html</item>
        <item>gactions — Google Actions Builder CLI. https://developers.google.com/assistant/conversational/df-asdk/actions-sdk/gactions-cli</item>
        <item>OpenAI Whisper / whisper-cli — OSS ASR for fixture transcription + comparison. pip install openai-whisper.</item>
        <item>ffmpeg — Mix utterance audio with ambient-noise stems for stress fixtures. distro package.</item>
        <item>sox — Pitch/speed perturbation to simulate accent/age variation. distro package.</item>
        <item>pytest-voice (custom harnesses) — Drive intent-resolution assertions in CI. n/a; build per-project.</item>
        <item>Voiceflow CLI — Export dialog model + test cases. https://www.voiceflow.com</item>
        <item>pyttsx3 / gTTS / ElevenLabs API — Synthesize test utterances at scale. pip install pyttsx3 gtts.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Alexa Developer Console + SMAPI (SaaS, yes) — Full REST API + ask-cli. Required for skill certification testing.</item>
        <item>Actions on Google + gactions (SaaS, yes) — Google Assistant simulator + logs.</item>
        <item>Voiceflow (SaaS, yes) — API for dialog export, test runs. Strong for prototype + regression suites.</item>
        <item>Bespoken (SaaS, yes) — CLI + Jest plugin. Voice-app testing platform; CI-friendly.</item>
        <item>Vocalize.ai (SaaS, partial) — Real-device farm, accent panels.</item>
        <item>Pulse Labs (SaaS, partial) — Booked panels. Real-user voice testing recruitment.</item>
        <item>Rasa (OSS, yes) — Full Python. Self-hosted NLU + test runner (rasa test).</item>
        <item>OpenAI Whisper / Deepgram / AssemblyAI (OSS / SaaS, yes) — ASR ground-truthing; Deepgram has streaming API.</item>
        <item>ElevenLabs (SaaS, yes) — API. High-quality TTS for fixture diversity.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Build the utterance corpus from real anonymized logs first, synthesize variants second; pure-LLM-generated corpora over-represent grammatical, in-domain phrasings.</item>
        <item>Track three accuracy tiers separately: ASR (word error rate), NLU (intent + slot F1), and dialog (task completion). A regression in only one tier tells you exactly where to look.</item>
        <item>Always include a "barge-in" test (user interrupts mid-prompt) and a "no input" test (timeout); these break dialog state machines more than utterance variation.</item>
        <item>Pin ASR model versions in CI — provider-side ASR upgrades silently shift WER and break tests overnight.</item>
        <item>For LLM-judge naturalness scoring, use pairwise comparison ("Is response A or B more natural?") not absolute 1-5 scores; pairwise is more reliable.</item>
        <item>Run the same suite in two locales minimum even for monolingual launches — reveals locale-leaking copy and fallback bugs.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Don't let the LLM-judge see the expected answer when scoring naturalness — anchoring bias inflates scores. Score blind, then compute correctness separately.</item>
        <item>ASR transcripts contain noise tokens ("[unintelligible]", "uh"); your assertion harness must normalize before exact-match. Use a fuzzy-match fallback with a logged threshold.</item>
        <item>Synthetic TTS used for fixtures may use the same vendor as your TTS output → false-high naturalness. Use a different TTS engine for fixtures than for product output.</item>
        <item>Latency: ASR + LLM judge per turn is slow. Parallelize per-test, but cap concurrency at provider rate limits or the suite hits 429s and silently passes.</item>
        <item>Cost: a 1000-utterance × 3-noise × 2-locale × LLM-judge sweep is non-trivial. Tier the suite: smoke (10 utterances, every commit) → full (nightly) → field-replay (release).</item>
        <item>Privacy: never send raw user-recorded audio to a cloud LLM judge. Transcribe first locally, redact PII, then judge the text.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="minimal-noise-injection-harness">
      <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# stress_corpus.sh — mix clean utterances with ambient noise stems at 3 SNRs
set -euo pipefail
CLEAN_DIR=fixtures/clean
NOISE_DIR=fixtures/noise   # cafe.wav, traffic.wav, tv.wav
OUT=fixtures/mixed
mkdir -p "$OUT"
for u in "$CLEAN_DIR"/*.wav; do
  for n in "$NOISE_DIR"/*.wav; do
    for snr in 20 10 5; do
      base="$(basename "$u" .wav)_$(basename "$n" .wav)_${snr}dB.wav"
      ffmpeg -y -i "$u" -i "$n" \
        -filter_complex "[1:a]volume=-${snr}dB[bg];[0:a][bg]amix=inputs=2:duration=first" \
        "$OUT/$base" 2>/dev/null
    done
  done
done
      ]]></code>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/test-plan.md" purpose="VUI test plan: objectives, fixture inventory, metric targets, CI tier schedule."/>
      <template path="templates/stress-corpus.sh" purpose="Shell script: mix clean utterances with ambient-noise stems at multiple SNR levels."/>
      <template path="templates/llm-judge-prompt.txt" purpose="Per-turn LLM judge prompt scoring intent_match, naturalness, brevity, error_recovery."/>
    </templates>

    <checklist>
      <check>ASR word-error rate is tracked separately from NLU and dialog metrics.</check>
      <check>Utterance corpus is built from real anonymized user logs first.</check>
      <check>Corpus includes barge-in tests (user interrupts mid-prompt).</check>
      <check>Corpus includes no-input tests (timeout).</check>
      <check>Noise injection covers at least three SNR levels (20dB, 10dB, 5dB).</check>
      <check>Suite is tiered: smoke (every commit), full (nightly), field-replay (release).</check>
      <check>Same suite runs in at least two locales.</check>
      <check>LLM-judge tier is blind to expected answers when scoring naturalness.</check>
      <check>TTS vendor for fixtures differs from product output vendor.</check>
      <check>Concurrency caps are set to prevent rate-limit hits.</check>
    </checklist>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/testing-voice-usability/"/>
      <link href="https://developer.amazon.com/en-US/docs/alexa/custom-skills/test-your-skill.html"/>
